<P>
GLENDALE / BURBANK FOCUS: BURBANK; CONSTRUCTION BEGINS ON VERDUGO TOWER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVE RYFLE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Burbank city officials on Monday celebrated the groundbreaking of Verdugo 
Tower, a 121-unit apartment building for needy seniors, which will be built 
with a $9.9-million loan from the federal Department of Housing and Urban 
Development. 
</P>
<P>
 The building, to be located at the northwest corner of Verdugo Avenue and San 
Fernando Road, is being built by the nonprofit corporation Verdugo Tower Inc., 
which also runs three other senior housing complexes in Burbank. 
</P>
<P>
 To be eligible for an apartment, applicants must be at least 62 years old and 
meet HUD income limitations and other requirements. Rent will equal 30% of the 
residents' adjusted gross income. 
</P>
<P>
 Construction of the eight-story building, which will have a 68-space 
underground parking garage and private balconies for some units, is expected to 
be finished in mid-1995. Project officials said they expect a flood of 
applications for apartments. A public drawing will be held a few months before 
the building opens. STEVE RYFLE 
</P>
</TEXT>
