<TEXT>
<P>
 A group of Cuban-American lawyers sued the United States government seeking an 
end to detention of Cuban refugees at Guantanamo Bay and Panama. About 32,000 
Cubans, all of them refugees picked up at sea this summer, are being held. 
Though the Clinton Administration has announced plans to allow some children 
and elderly Cuban refugees to enter the United States, the others must remain 
at the U.S. bases indefinitely or return to Cuba to apply for some of the 
20,000 visas per year available to Cubans. 
