<HEADLINE>
<P>
OXNARD SHOOTING LEAVES 1 DEAD, 1 CRITICALLY WOUNDED; CRIME: POLICE SAY THEY ARE 
SEARCHING FOR A SUSPECT WHO FLED THE APARTMENT AND WAS KNOWN BY THE VICTIMS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MAIA DAVIS and JULIE FIELDS, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A shooting in a south Oxnard apartment left one man dead and another 
critically wounded Monday afternoon, as police searched for at least one 
suspect who fled the scene, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
 Oxnard firefighters found Jerome Hurst, 25, of Oxnard dead on the living room 
floor of the apartment in the 1400 block of Friedrich Lane shortly before 2 
p.m., authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
 Vernon Hunter, 27, who lives at the apartment with his girlfriend and two 
children, was found outside lying on a neighbor's doorstep bleeding from 
multiple gunshot wounds. 
</P>
<P>
 Hunter underwent surgery at St. John's Regional Medical Center and was listed 
in critical condition Monday night, a hospital spokeswoman said. 
</P>
<P>
 Responding to calls from neighbors who heard gunshots and Hunter's cries for 
help, firefighters first found Hunter and then discovered Hurst's body inside 
the apartment after asking neighbors where Hunter lived, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
 Hurst, who worked at Furr's Cafeteria on Channel Islands Boulevard, was shot 
multiple times in his upper body, police said. He was dead by the time 
firefighters arrived. 
</P>
<P>
 "There were no vital signs," Oxnard Fire Capt. George Todd said. "We connected 
him to a heart monitor and it was flat-lined." 
</P>
<P>
 Hunter was also shot multiple times. 
</P>
<P>
 Todd said it appeared Hunter had been shot three times, twice in the back and 
once on the side of the neck. One of the bullets passed through Hunter's body 
and exited through his chest, he said. 
</P>
<P>
 Despite the wounds, Hunter managed to get out of the apartment. "He staggered 
outside to a neighbor's door and banged on the door," Todd said. 
</P>
<P>
 And he was able to tell authorities about the shooting, Police Sgt. Charles 
Dunham said. 
</P>
<P>
 The shooting was not gang- or drug-related, Dunham said. Police also said 
neither Hunter nor Hurst had been robbed. But the victims knew the person who 
shot them, he said. 
</P>
<P>
 "This person showed up and shot them," Dunham said. But, first, "there was an 
exchange" of words. "We're still trying to identify the person we're looking 
for," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 Dunham also said police believe they know the motive behind the shooting, 
although he refused to disclose it. 
</P>
<P>
 Neighbors said Hunter, his girlfriend and her young son and daughter had moved 
to the apartment complex about six months ago. 
</P>
<P>
 The children often played outside with neighbors' youngsters. And residents 
said they saw Hunter, who friends said is currently unemployed, working on his 
car in the back alley. 
</P>
<P>
 "They're very good neighbors," Maria Garibay said. "We've never had problems 
with them." 
</P>
</TEXT>
