<HEADLINE>
<P>
CLIPPER UPDATE; AN UNTIMELY COURT DATE FOR ROBERTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHRIS BAKER, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Clipper center Stanley Roberts, who began working out with the team last 
Friday after reporting to camp overweight, will skip the final two days of 
two-a-day workouts because he had to fly to Raleigh, N.C., Monday morning for 
an appearance today in traffic court. 
</P>
<P>
 Roberts, who got a speeding ticket while he was at the Duke Diet and Fitness 
Center last summer, was ordered to appear after failing to appear at the 
original hearing. 
</P>
<P>
 Clipper officials were not happy about Roberts' absence. 
</P>
<P>
 Coach Bill Fitch said Roberts did extra work at Sunday night's practice and 
was given a conditioning program to follow while he is away. 
</P>
<P>
 "We gave him an extra dose when the rest of the guys were taking naps," Fitch 
said. "But he'll miss the scrimmage part. He'll miss two conditioning 
(workouts), but we've been double hard on him. He's got a routine he has to do 
while he's on the road." 
</P>
<P>
 Fitch also thinks he might have cured Roberts of speeding. 
</P>
<P>
 After seeing him speed out of the parking lot after a Clipper practice, Fitch 
ordered Roberts to run extra laps as punishment. Clipper Notes 
</P>
<P>
 Forward Harold Ellis sprained his right ankle when he landed awkwardly when he 
tried to block a shot in a scrimmage Monday night. The severity of the injury 
was not immediately known, but Ellis was taken to an emergency room for X-rays, 
which were negative. Ellis, who had never sprained an ankle before, was in 
considerable pain. He thinks the injury might have occurred because he was 
wearing new shoes that offered no ankle support. . . . Rookie forward Lamond 
Murray, who signed a $13.5-million, five-year contract Friday, is expected to 
make his NBA debut in Wednesday night's exhibition against the Atlanta Hawks at 
the Sports Arena. . . . Terry Dehere, who was drafted as a shooting guard last 
season, was used at point guard in Saturday's 114-109 exhibition victory over 
the Sacramento Kings. 
</P>
